div.p:
That where true grace is, there is a proceeding;
                        Doct. True grace hath its proceedings. though it be but weake, and can scarse creepe, yet when God puts vnder it his stilts, his crutches, it will take the aduantage of them, and will be going: Examine we therfore our faith by this; If it be more liuely, after more liuely and effectuall meanes, as here this their faith after the Miracle. As wee see how after some plentifull showre the grasse sprouts forth lustily, that before was very short. 1 Ioh. 5.13. These things haue I written to you that beleeue, that ye

 may beleeue, namely, more strongly: So here did Christ worke this Miracle before his beleeuing Disciples, that they might beleeue. So should it be with Christians, after a good Sermon, after some speciall worke of Gods mercy or iustice, to gather strength. A poore horse that goes slowly, yet when well baited and refreshed, will goe freshly, and then we say, Now he goes, as if he went not before: So a dead fire, when quickned with the bellowes, will cast forth a greater hear, & then we say, Now it burnes, and yet it burnt before. A christian must not be discouraged if he finde some dulnes, & deadnes, & weaknes in his faith, so be it when God comes with his baite, with his bellowes, with his showres, he feele spirit & quickning. But then is the discouragement, when our faith sleeping, cannot be awakened with those blessed means God vseth.

2. Point. The Scripture it selfe remembred;
                        Doctr. Christians must be zealous for the good of the Church.
                     The zeale of thine house hath eaten mee vp: Where Dauids, and in his, Christs zeale is set forth: First, by the matter of it; The zeale of thine house: Secondly, the manner, vehement and violent, like fire that eates vp and deuoures that whereon it lights.

Marke how Christ speakes to Nicodemus in the 
                        Doct. 3 plurall number, Yee receiue not;
                     Ministers are oftentimes guilty of peoples sinnes. blaming him that was a teacher for the infidelitie of the people: So, Reuel. 2. and 3. all the blame of the Churches is laid vpon the Angels of the seuerall Churches. Diogenes seeing a Scholler behaue himselfe vnhappily, strucke his Master. It is Aaron that hath made the people naked: and from the Prophets of Ierusalem is wickednesse gone forth into the whole land, Ier. 23.15. Let all Ministers, Magistrates, and Superiours, that stand charged with others, thinke of the weightinesse of their charge, and strictnesse of their account, and tremble.

In Faith there is a certaine and grounded knowledge; 
                        Doct. 3
                     We haue heard our selues & know, &c. Ioh. 6.69. Wee beleeue and know. Hence Knowledge put for Faith, Iohn 17.3. This makes against both the implicite Romish faith, and the staggering wauering faith of many among our selues.
